 shove, tug, yank) that do not have an inherent semantic component of &amp;quot;separating&amp;quot; belong to this class because of the component of force in their meaning.
    They are interpretable as verbs of splitting or separating only in particular syntactic frames (I pulled the twig and the branch apart, I pulled the twig off (of) the branch, but not *I pulled the twig and the branch).
    The adjunction of the apart adverb adds a change of state semantic component with respect to the object which is not present otherwise.
    These fringe split verbs appear in several other intersective classes that highlight the force aspect of their meaning.
    Figure 2 depicts the intersection of split, carry and push/pull.
